            "created_at": "2018-05-22T16:58:47Z",
            "updated_at": "2018-05-22T16:58:47Z",
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> as it would break loads of small hobby projects\r\n\r\nit would break the majority of projects when they are executed locally via `flask run` or `app.run()` during development. At the very least, this should be done only when the app runs in production mode.\r\n\r\n> We can turn on the secure option when request.is_secure\r\n\r\nNote that in many deployment situations the SSL connection does not reach the Flask app because it is terminated at a proxy server. In those cases, `request.is_secure` will apply to the connection between the proxy server and the Flask app which is not secure. You can apply the `ProxyFix` middleware along with some configuration in the proxy server to correct this, but in my experience very few people do this.\r\n\r\nMy concern with an automatic secure flag is that it may make people think they're secure, while in fact, with a default proxy server configuration they won't be."
        },
