            "updated_at": "2018-05-22T20:52:55Z",
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "The way I see it, default behavior depends on what is the primary intended use for Flask. If the answer is user facing websites/applications served over web (-> in most cases going through public wifis etc.), then I hope Flask would default to the more 'safe' option (with the ability to override it). \r\n\r\nIf I look back at myself starting, I'd expect the defaults to provide as much security as possible and if something wasn't working because I wasn't following the most secure pracitces, I would learn something new (and important), consider whether my use case really can break this. With the default being false, I'm thinking \"smarter people than me wrote it\" and it never comes into question. It would be really interesting to collect the data on how many publicly accessible flask based websites don't realize it and don't have the session cookie secure. It's not something you notice easily.\r\n\r\nPersonally I don't like to rely on dynamic behavior based on seemingly unrelated options like the all powerful debug mode, or in some cases unreliable `is_secure`. \r\n\r\n###### Somewhat unrelated fun fact: Until today I didn't realize that the session is only signed by the app key, I always thought everything in it was hashed with the key as a salt, meaning I could store secret-ish stuff in there."
        },
