            "created_at": "2018-05-22T21:21:29Z",
            "updated_at": "2018-05-22T21:21:29Z",
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Based on Miguel's investigation, going to close this for now.\r\n\r\nI'm not sure how users would even discover what's happening if this was changed. From their perspective all that happens is they never receive the cookie. The vast majority of users are new, I guarantee that most users, past me included, would have a very hard time determining that they weren't receiving cookies because of this setting. See the related issue of Chrome not storing cookies for localhost in some circumstances for evidence of that.\r\n\r\nSecure-by-default is good, but I think the actual surface exposed by this is rather low compared to the issues it will cause during development. I'd rather people understand their system and security needs when they're deploying, and understand the configuration available to them.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nThe default cookie is secure from tampering, not from inspection. If you want to store private data in the session, you need to use a different session implementation, either an encrypted cookie or server-side storage. Maybe that can be made more clear in the docs?"
